# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chaos-engineering-tools
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Learn the history behind Chaos Engineering, how to apply it, and how it helps improve reliability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] We strive to keep all tutorials current.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] However, this tutorial has not been updated recently and may contain out-of-date instructions.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] With the rise of microservices and distributed cloud architectures, the web has grown increasingly complex.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] We all depend on these systems more than ever, yet failures have become much harder to predict.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] These failures cause costly outages for companies.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] The outages hurt customers trying to shop, transact business, and get work done.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Even brief outages can impact a company's bottom line, so the cost of downtime is becoming a KPI for many engineering teams.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] For example, in 2017, 98% of organizations said a single hour of downtime would cost their business over $100,000.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] One outage can cost a single company millions of dollars.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] The CEO of British Airways recently explained how one failure that stranded tens of thousands of British Airways (BA) passengers in May 2017 cost the company 80 million pounds ($102.19 million USD).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Companies need a solution to this challenge—waiting for the next costly outage is not an option.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] To meet the challenge head on, more and more companies are turning to Chaos Engineering.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Chaos Engineering is a disciplined approach to identifying failures before they become outages.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] By proactively testing how a system responds under stress, you can identify and fix failures before they end up in the news.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Chaos Engineering lets you compare what you think will happen to what actually happens in your systems.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] You literally “break things on purpose” to learn how to build more resilient systems.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] (If you’re here to get started with Chaos Engineering, you can get free access to all of Gremlin for 30 days.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Chaos Engineering involves running thoughtful, planned experiments that teach us how our systems behave in the face of failure.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] You start by forming a hypothesis about how a system should behave when something goes wrong.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Then, you design the smallest possible experiment to test it in your system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Finally, you measure the impact of the failure at each step, looking for signs of success or failure.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] When the experiment is over, you have a better understanding of your system's real-world behavior.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Many larger tech companies practice Chaos Engineering to better understand their distributed systems and microservice architectures.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] The list includes Twilio, Netflix, LinkedIn, Facebook, Google, Microsoft, Amazon, and many others.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] But more traditional industries, like banking and finance, have caught on to Chaos Engineering, too.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] For example, in 2014, the National Australia Bank migrated from physical infrastructure to Amazon Web Services and used Chaos Engineering to dramatically reduce incident counts.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] The Chaos Engineering Slack Community has created a diagram that tracks known Chaos Engineering tools and known engineers working on Chaos Engineering.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Think of a vaccine or a flu shot, where you inject yourself with a small amount of a potentially harmful foreign body in order to build resistance and prevent illness.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Chaos Engineering is a tool we use to build such an immunity in our technical systems by injecting harm (like latency, CPU failure, or network black holes) in order to find and mitigate potential weaknesses.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] These experiments have the added benefit of helping teams build muscle memory in resolving outages, akin to a fire drill (or changing a flat tire, in the Netflix analogy).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] By breaking things on purpose we surface unknown issues that could impact our systems and customers.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] According to the 2021 State of Chaos Engineering report, the most common outcomes of Chaos Engineering are increased availability, lower mean time to resolution (MTTR), lower mean time to detection (MTTD), fewer bugs shipped to product, and fewer outages.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Teams who frequently run Chaos Engineering experiments are more likely to have >99.9% availability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Distributed systems are inherently more complex than monolithic systems, so it’s hard to predict all the ways they might fail.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] The eight fallacies of distributed systems shared by Peter Deutsch and others at Sun Microsystems describe false assumptions that programmers new to distributed applications invariably make.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Many of these fallacies drive the design of Chaos Engineering experiments such as “packet-loss attacks” and “latency attacks”.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] For example, network outages can cause a range of failures for applications that severely impact customers.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Applications may stall while they wait endlessly for a packet.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Applications may permanently consume memory or other Linux system resources.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] And even after a network outage has passed, applications may fail to retry stalled operations, or may retry too aggressively.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Applications may even require a manual restart.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Each of these examples need to be tested and prepared for.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Many engineering organizations, including Netflix and Stitch Fix, have dedicated Chaos Engineering teams.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] These teams are often small in size, with 2—5 engineers.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] The Chaos Engineering team owns and advocates for Chaos Engineering across the organization.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] However, they are not the only engineers doing Chaos Engineering day-to-day—they empower teams across their engineering organization to use Chaos Engineering.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Some companies, such as Remind, are integrating Chaos Engineering into their normal release cycle like other best practice testing as a way to ensure reliability is baked into every feature.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] To illustrate this in practice with examples, we will demonstrate how to select experiments based on a sharded MySQL Database.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] In this example, we have a cluster of 100 MySQL hosts with multiple shards per host.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] In one region, we have a primary database host with two replicas and we use semi-sync replication.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] We also have a pseudo primary and two pseudo replicas in a different region.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] **Known-Unknowns:** Use the results and data of the known-known experiment to answer questions which would currently be “known-unknowns”.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] You will now be able to know the impact the weekly average of the mean time it takes from experiencing a failure to adding a clone back to the cluster effectively.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] You will also know if 5 minutes is an appropriate alerting threshold to prevent SEVs.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] **Unknown-Knowns:** Increase the number of replicas to four before conducting this experiment.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Shutdown two replicas for a cluster at the same time, collect the mean time during a Monday morning over several months to determine how long it would take us to clone two new replicas off the existing primary.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] This experiment may identify unknown issues, for example, the primary cannot handle the load from cloning and backups at the same time and you need to make better use of the replicas.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] **Unknown-Unknowns:** Shut down of an entire cluster (primary and two replicas) would require engineering work to make this possible.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] This failure may occur unexpectedly in the wild, but you are not yet ready to handle it.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Prioritize the engineering work to handle this failure scenario before you perform chaos experiments.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] One of the most powerful questions in Chaos Engineering is “What could go wrong?”.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] By asking this question about our services and environments, we can review potential weaknesses and discuss expected outcomes.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Similar to a risk assessment, this informs priorities about which scenarios are more likely (or more frightening) and should be tested first.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] By sitting down as a team and whiteboarding your service(s), dependencies (both internal and external), and data stores, you can formulate a picture of “What could go wrong?”.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] When in doubt, injecting a failure or a delay into each of your dependencies is a great place to start.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] You have chosen the exact failure to inject.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] This is an excellent thought exercise to work through as a team.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] By discussing the scenario, you can hypothesize on the expected outcome before running it live.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] What will be the impact to customers, to your service, or to your dependencies?
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] To understand how your system behaves under stress, you need to measure your system’s availability and durability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] It is good to have a key performance metric that correlates to customer success (such as orders per minute, or stream starts per second).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] As a rule of thumb, if you ever see an impact to these metrics, you want to halt the experiment immediately.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Next is measuring the failure itself where you want to verify (or disprove) your hypothesis.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] This could be the impact on latency, requests per second, or system resources.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Lastly, you want to survey your dashboards and alarms for unintended side effects.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Always have a backup plan in case things go wrong, but accept that sometimes even the backup plan can fail.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Talk through how you’re going to revert the impact.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] If you’re running commands by hand, be thoughtful not to break ssh or control plane access to your instances.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] One of the core aspects of Gremlin is safety.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] All of our attacks can be reverted immediately, allowing you to safely abort and return to steady state if things go wrong.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] After running your first experiment, hopefully, there is one of two outcomes: either you’ve verified that your system is resilient to the failure you introduced, or you’ve found a problem you need to fix.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] On one hand, you’ve increased your confidence in the system and its behavior, and on the other you’ve found a problem before it caused an outage.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Chaos Engineering is a tool to make your job easier.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] By proactively testing and validating your system’s failure modes you will reduce your operational burden, increase your availability, and sleep better at night.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering-the-history-principles-and-practice] Gremlin makes it safe and simple to get started—email us to get started today!
