[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] In software development, the ability of a given software to tolerate failures while still ensuring adequate quality of service—often termed *resilience*—is typically specified as a requirement.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] However, development teams may fail to meet this requirement due to factors such as short deadlines or lack of domain knowledge.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] Chaos engineering encompasses techniques aimed at meeting resilience requirements.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] Chaos engineering can be used to achieve resilience against infrastructure failures, network failures, and application failures; the latter includes resilience to unhandled exceptions.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] Calculating how much confidence we have in the interconnected complex systems that are put into production environments requires operational readiness metrics.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] Operational readiness can be evaluated using chaos engineering simulations.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] Solutions for increasing the resilience and operational readiness of a platform include strengthening the backup, restore, network file transfer, failover capabilities and overall security of the environment.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] An evaluation to induce chaos in a Kubernetes environment terminated random pods receiving data from edge devices in data centers while processing analytics on a big data network.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] The pods' recovery time was a resiliency metric that estimated the response time.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] While MacWrite and MacPaint were being developed for the first Apple Macintosh computer, Steve Capps created "Monkey", a desk accessory which randomly generated user interface events at high speed, simulating a monkey frantically banging the keyboard and moving and clicking the mouse.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] It was promptly put to use for debugging by generating errors for programmers to fix, because automated testing was not possible; the first Macintosh had too little free memory space for anything more sophisticated.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] While working to improve website reliability at Amazon, Jesse Robbins created "Game day", an initiative that increases reliability by purposefully creating major failures on a regular basis.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] Robbins has said it was inspired by firefighter training and research in other fields lessons in complex systems, reliability engineering.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] While at Google, Kripa Krishnan created a similar program to Amazon's Game day (see above) called "DiRT" (Disaster Recovery Testing).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] Jason Cahoon, a Site Reliability Engineer at Google, contributed a chapter on Google DiRT in the "Chaos Engineering" book and described the system at the GOTOpia 2021 conference.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] While overseeing Netflix's migration to the cloud in 2011 Nora Jones, Casey Rosenthal, and Greg Orzell expanded the discipline while working together at Netflix by setting up a tool that would cause breakdowns in their production environment, the environment used by Netflix customers.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] By regularly "killing" random instances of a software service, it was possible to test a redundant architecture to verify that a server failure did not noticeably impact customers.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] The concept of chaos engineering is close to the one of Phoenix Servers, first introduced by Martin Fowler in 2012.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] The code behind Chaos Monkey was released by Netflix in 2012 under an Apache 2.0 license.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] Voyages-sncf.com's 2017 "Day of Chaos" gamified simulating pre-production failures to present at the 2017 DevOps REX conference.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] Founded in 2019, Steadybit popularized pre-production chaos and reliability engineering.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] Its open-source Reliability Hub extends Steadybit.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] Proofdock can inject infrastructure, platform, and application failures on Microsoft Azure DevOps.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] Gremlin is a "failure-as-a-service" platform.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/chaos-engineering] Facebook's Project Storm simulates datacenter failures for natural disaster resistance.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] In computer science, **fault injection** is a testing technique for understanding how computing systems behave when stressed in unusual ways.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] This can be achieved using physical- or software-based means, or using a hybrid approach.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Widely studied physical fault injections include the application of high voltages, extreme temperatures and electromagnetic pulses on electronic components, such as computer memory and central processing units.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] By exposing components to conditions beyond their intended operating limits, computing systems can be coerced into mis-executing instructions and corrupting critical data.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] In software testing, fault injection is a technique for improving the coverage of a test by introducing faults to test code paths; in particular error handling code paths, that might otherwise rarely be followed.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] It is often used with stress testing and is widely considered to be an important part of developing robust software.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Robustness testing (also known as syntax testing, fuzzing or fuzz testing) is a type of fault injection commonly used to test for vulnerabilities in communication interfaces such as protocols, command line parameters, or APIs.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] The propagation of a fault through to an observable failure follows a well-defined cycle.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] When executed, a fault may cause an error, which is an invalid state within a system boundary.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] An error may cause further errors within the system boundary, therefore each new error acts as a fault, or it may propagate to the system boundary and be observable.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] When error states are observed at the system boundary they are termed failures.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] This mechanism is termed the fault-error-failure cycle and is a key mechanism in dependability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] The technique of fault injection dates back to the 1970s when it was first used to induce faults at a hardware level.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] This type of fault injection is called Hardware Implemented Fault Injection (HWIFI) and attempts to simulate hardware failures within a system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] The first experiments in hardware fault involved nothing more than shorting connections on circuit boards and observing the effect on the system (bridging faults).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] It was used primarily as a test of the dependability of the hardware system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Later specialised hardware was developed to extend this technique, such as devices to bombard specific areas of a circuit board with heavy radiation.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] It was soon found that faults could be induced by software techniques and that aspects of this technique could be useful for assessing software systems.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Collectively these techniques are known as Software Implemented Fault Injection (SWIFI).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] SWIFI techniques can be categorized into two types: compile-time injection and runtime injection.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Code mutation produces faults which are very similar to those unintentionally added by programmers.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] A refinement of code mutation is *Code Insertion Fault Injection* which adds code, rather than modifying existing code.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] In this case, pFunc is the perturbation function and it is applied to the return value of the function that has been called introducing a fault into the system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Runtime injection techniques can use a number of different techniques to insert faults into a system via a trigger.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] These techniques are often based around the debugging facilities provided by computer processor architectures.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Fuzzing is an especially useful form of Black-box testing since the various invalid inputs that are submitted to the software system do not depend on, and are not created based on knowledge of, the details of the code running inside the system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] This technique is based on a nail bed, necessary to contact the electronics of the products, where a specific test pad has been left free (Design for testability of PCB), and properly inject disturbance signals, in order to see the product's control- reaction arm's reaction if present.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] It's a technique often used to certify and validate reaction to fault in high reliability products, where safety is involved (Military, Medical, Autonomous vehicle).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Because of the wide complexity a dedicated and complex tools is necessary.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] These parameters create the fault space realm.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] The fault space realm will increase exponentially by increasing system complexity.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Therefore, the traditional fault injection method will not be applicable to use in the modern cyber-physical systems, because they will be so slow, and they will find a small number of faults (less fault coverage).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Hence, the testers need an efficient algorithm to choose critical faults that have a higher impact on system behavior.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Thus, the main research question is how to find critical faults in the fault space realm which have catastrophic effects on system behavior.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Here are some methods that can aid fault injection to efficiently explore the fault space to reach higher fault coverage in less simulation time.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Although these types of faults can be injected by hand the possibility of introducing an unintended fault is high, so tools exist to parse a program automatically and insert faults.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] A number of SWIFI Tools have been developed and a selection of these tools is given here.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Six commonly used fault injection tools are Ferrari, FTAPE, Doctor, Orchestra, Xception and Grid-FIT.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] In contrast to traditional mutation testing where mutant faults are generated and injected into the code description of the model, application of a series of newly defined mutation operators directly to the model properties rather than to the model code has also been investigated.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Mutant properties that are generated from the initial properties (or test cases) and validated by the model checker should be considered as new properties that have been missed during the initial verification procedure.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Therefore, adding these newly identified properties to the existing list of properties improves the coverage metric of the formal verification and consequently lead to a more reliable design.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] In the testing of operating systems for example, fault injection is often performed by a *driver* (kernel-mode software) that intercepts *system calls* (calls into the kernel) and randomly returning a failure for some of the calls.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] This type of fault injection is useful for testing low-level user-mode software.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] For higher level software, various methods inject faults.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] In managed code, it is common to use instrumentation.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Although fault injection can be undertaken by hand, a number of fault injection tools exist to automate the process of fault injection.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Depending on the complexity of the API for the level where faults are injected, fault injection tests often must be carefully designed to minimize the number of false positives.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Even a well designed fault injection test can sometimes produce situations that are impossible in the normal operation of the software.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] For example, imagine there are two API functions, `Commit` and `PrepareForCommit`, such that alone, each of these functions can possibly fail, but if `PrepareForCommit` is called and succeeds, a subsequent call to `Commit` is guaranteed to succeed.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] Often, it will be infeasible for the fault injection implementation to keep track of enough state to make the guarantee that the API functions make.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/fault-injection] In this example, a fault injection test of the above code might hit the assert, whereas this would never happen in normal operation.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Advances in large-scale, distributed software systems are changing the game for software engineering.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] As an industry, we are quick to adopt practices that increase flexibility of development and velocity of deployment.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] An urgent question follows on the heels of these benefits: How much confidence we can have in the complex systems that we put into production?
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Even when all of the individual services in a distributed system are functioning properly, the interactions between those services can cause unpredictable outcomes.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Unpredictable outcomes, compounded by rare but disruptive real-world events that affect production environments, make these distributed systems inherently chaotic.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] We need to identify weaknesses before they manifest in system-wide, aberrant behaviors.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Systemic weaknesses could take the form of: improper fallback settings when a service is unavailable; retry storms from improperly tuned timeouts; outages when a downstream dependency receives too much traffic; cascading failures when a single point of failure crashes; etc.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] We must address the most significant weaknesses proactively, before they affect our customers in production.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] We need a way to manage the chaos inherent in these systems, take advantage of increasing flexibility and velocity, and have confidence in our production deployments despite the complexity that they represent.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] An empirical, systems-based approach addresses the chaos in distributed systems at scale and builds confidence in the ability of those systems to withstand realistic conditions.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] We learn about the behavior of a distributed system by observing it during a controlled experiment.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] To specifically address the uncertainty of distributed systems at scale, Chaos Engineering can be thought of as the facilitation of experiments to uncover systemic weaknesses.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Hypothesize that this steady state will continue in both the control group and the experimental group.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Introduce variables that reflect real world events like servers that crash, hard drives that malfunction, network connections that are severed, etc.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Try to disprove the hypothesis by looking for a difference in steady state between the control group and the experimental group.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] The harder it is to disrupt the steady state, the more confidence we have in the behavior of the system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] If a weakness is uncovered, we now have a target for improvement before that behavior manifests in the system at large.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] The following principles describe an ideal application of Chaos Engineering, applied to the processes of experimentation described above.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] The degree to which these principles are pursued strongly correlates to the confidence we can have in a distributed system at scale.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Focus on the measurable output of a system, rather than internal attributes of the system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Measurements of that output over a short period of time constitute a proxy for the system’s steady state.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] The overall system’s throughput, error rates, latency percentiles, etc. could all be metrics of interest representing steady state behavior.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] By focusing on systemic behavior patterns during experiments, Chaos verifies that the system does work, rather than trying to validate how it works.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Chaos variables reflect real-world events.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Prioritize events either by potential impact or estimated frequency.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Consider events that correspond to hardware failures like servers dying, software failures like malformed responses, and non-failure events like a spike in traffic or a scaling event.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Any event capable of disrupting steady state is a potential variable in a Chaos experiment.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Systems behave differently depending on environment and traffic patterns.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Since the behavior of utilization can change at any time, sampling real traffic is the only way to reliably capture the request path.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] To guarantee both authenticity of the way in which the system is exercised and relevance to the current deployed system, Chaos strongly prefers to experiment directly on production traffic.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Running experiments manually is labor-intensive and ultimately unsustainable.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Automate experiments and run them continuously.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Chaos Engineering builds automation into the system to drive both orchestration and analysis.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Experimenting in production has the potential to cause unnecessary customer pain.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] While there must be an allowance for some short-term negative impact, it is the responsibility and obligation of the Chaos Engineer to ensure the fallout from experiments are minimized and contained.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Chaos Engineering is a powerful practice that is already changing how software is designed and engineered at some of the largest-scale operations in the world.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Where other practices address velocity and flexibility, Chaos specifically tackles systemic uncertainty in these distributed systems.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] The Principles of Chaos provide confidence to innovate quickly at massive scales and give customers the high quality experiences they deserve.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/principlesofchaos-org] Join the ongoing discussion of the Principles of Chaos and their application in the Chaos Community.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The *reliability function* is theoretically defined as the probability of success.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] In practice, it is calculated using different techniques, and its value ranges between 0 and 1, where 0 indicates no probability of success while 1 indicates definite success.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] This probability is estimated from detailed (physics of failure) analysis, previous data sets, or through reliability testing and reliability modeling.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability, testability, maintainability, and maintenance are often defined as a part of "reliability engineering" in reliability programs.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability often plays a vital role in the cost-effectiveness of overall systems.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering deals with the prediction, prevention, and management of high levels of "lifetime" engineering uncertainty and risks of failure.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Although stochastic parameters define and affect reliability, reliability is not only achieved by mathematics and statistics.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering relates closely to quality engineering, safety engineering, and system safety, in that they use common methods for their analysis and may require input from each other.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] It can be said that a system must be reliably safe.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering focuses on the costs of failure caused by the system downtime, cost of spares, repair equipment, personnel, and cost of warranty claims.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The word *reliability* can be traced back to 1816 and is first attested to the poet Samuel Taylor Coleridge.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Before World War II the term was linked mostly to repeatability; a test (in any type of science) was considered "reliable" if the same results would be obtained repeatedly.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1920s, product improvement through the use of statistical process control was promoted by Dr.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Shewhart at Bell Labs, around the time that Waloddi Weibull was working on statistical models for fatigue.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The development of reliability engineering was here on a parallel path with quality.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The modern use of the word reliability was defined by the U.S. military in the 1940s, characterizing a product that would operate when expected and for a specified period.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] In World War II, many reliability issues stemmed from the inherent unreliability of electronic equipment available at the time and from fatigue.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Miner published a seminal paper titled "Cumulative Damage in Fatigue" in an ASME journal.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] A main application for reliability engineering in the military was for the vacuum tube as used in radar systems and other electronics, for which reliability proved to be very problematic and costly.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The IEEE formed the Reliability Society in 1948.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] In 1950, the United States Department of Defense formed a group called the "Advisory Group on the Reliability of Electronic Equipment" (AGREE) to investigate reliability methods for military equipment.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1960s, more emphasis was given to reliability testing on component and system levels.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The famous military standard MIL-STD-781 was created at that time.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Around this period also the much-used predecessor to military handbook 217 was published by RCA and was used for the prediction of failure rates of electronic components.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The emphasis on component reliability and empirical research (e.g.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] More pragmatic approaches, as used in the consumer industries, were being used.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1980s, televisions were increasingly made up of solid-state semiconductors.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Automobiles rapidly increased their use of semiconductors with a variety of microcomputers under the hood and in the dash.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Large air conditioning systems developed electronic controllers, as did microwave ovens and a variety of other appliances.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Communications systems began to adopt electronics to replace older mechanical switching systems.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Bellcore issued the first consumer prediction methodology for telecommunications, and SAE developed a similar document SAE870050 for automotive applications.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The nature of predictions evolved during the decade, and it became apparent that die complexity wasn't the only factor that determined failure rates for integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Kam Wong published a paper questioning the bathtub curve—see also reliability-centered maintenance.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] During this decade, the failure rate of many components dropped by a factor of 10.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Software became important to the reliability of systems.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] By the 1990s, the pace of IC development was picking up.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Wider use of stand-alone microcomputers was common, and the PC market helped keep IC densities following Moore's law and doubling about every 18 months.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering was now changing as it moved towards understanding the physics of failure.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure rates for components kept dropping, but system-level issues became more prominent.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems thinking has become more and more important.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] For software, the CMM model (Capability Maturity Model) was developed, which gave a more qualitative approach to reliability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] ISO 9000 added reliability measures to the design and development portion of certification.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The expansion of the World Wide Web created new challenges of security and trust.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The older problem of too little reliable information available had now been replaced by too much information of questionable value.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Consumer reliability problems could now be discussed online in real-time using data.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] New technologies such as micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS), handheld GPS, and hand-held devices that combine cell phones and computers all represent challenges to maintaining reliability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Product development time continued to shorten through this decade and what had been done in three years was being done in 18 months.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] This meant that reliability tools and tasks had to be more closely tied to the development process itself.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] In many ways, reliability has become part of everyday life and consumer expectations.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is the probability of a product performing its intended function under specified operating conditions in a manner that meets or exceeds customer expectations.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] To identify and correct the causes of failures that do occur despite the efforts to prevent them.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] To determine ways of coping with failures that do occur, if their causes have not been corrected.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] To apply methods for estimating the likely reliability of new designs, and for analysing reliability data.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason for the priority emphasis is that it is by far the most effective way of working, in terms of minimizing costs and generating reliable products.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The primary skills that are required, therefore, are the ability to understand and anticipate the possible causes of failures, and knowledge of how to prevent them.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] It is also necessary to know the methods that can be used for analyzing designs and data.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering for "complex systems" requires a different, more elaborate systems approach than for non-complex systems.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] These analyses must be done properly and with much attention to detail to be effective.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Consistent with the creation of safety cases, for example per ARP4761, the goal of reliability assessments is to provide a robust set of qualitative and quantitative evidence that the use of a component or system will not be associated with unacceptable risk.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk here is the combination of probability and severity of the failure incident (scenario) occurring.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The severity can be looked at from a system safety or a system availability point of view.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability for safety can be thought of as a very different focus from reliability for system availability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability and safety can exist in dynamic tension as keeping a system too available can be unsafe.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Forcing an engineering system into a safe state too quickly can force false alarms that impede the availability of the system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] In a *de minimis* definition, the severity of failures includes the cost of spare parts, man-hours, logistics, damage (secondary failures), and downtime of machines which may cause production loss.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] What is acceptable is determined by the managing authority or customers or the affected communities.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Residual risk is the risk that is left over after all reliability activities have finished, and includes the unidentified risk—and is therefore not completely quantifiable.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The complexity of the technical systems such as improvements of design and materials, planned inspections, fool-proof design, and backup redundancy decreases risk and increases the cost.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk can be decreased to ALARA (as low as reasonably achievable) or ALAPA (as low as practically achievable) levels.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Implementing a reliability program is not simply a software purchase; it is not just a checklist of items that must be completed that ensure one has reliable products and processes.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program is a complex learning and knowledge-based system unique to one's products and processes.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] It is supported by leadership, built on the skills that one develops within a team, integrated into business processes, and executed by following proven standard work practices.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is used to document exactly what "best practices" (tasks, methods, tools, analysis, and tests) are required for a particular (sub)system, as well as clarify customer requirements for reliability assessment.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] For large-scale complex systems, the reliability program plan should be a separate document.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Resource determination for manpower and budgets for testing and other tasks is critical for a successful program.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] In general, the amount of work required for an effective program for complex systems is large.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is essential for achieving high levels of reliability, testability, maintainability, and the resulting system availability, and is developed early during system development and refined over the system's life cycle.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] It specifies not only what the reliability engineer does, but also the tasks performed by other stakeholders.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] An effective reliability program plan must be approved by top program management, which is responsible for the allocation of sufficient resources for its implementation.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan may also be used to evaluate and improve the availability of a system by the strategy of focusing on increasing testability & maintainability and not on reliability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Improving maintainability is generally easier than improving reliability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability estimates (repair rates) are also generally more accurate.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] However, because the uncertainties in the reliability estimates are in most cases very large, they are likely to dominate the availability calculation (prediction uncertainty problem), even when maintainability levels are very high.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] When reliability is not under control, more complicated issues may arise, like manpower (maintainers/customer service capability) shortages, spare part availability, logistic delays, lack of repair facilities, extensive retrofit and complex configuration management costs, and others.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The problem of unreliability may be increased also due to the "domino effect" of maintenance-induced failures after repairs.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Focusing only on maintainability is therefore not enough.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] If failures are prevented, none of the other issues are of any importance, and therefore reliability is generally regarded as the most important part of availability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability needs to be evaluated and improved related to both availability and the total cost of ownership (TCO) due to the cost of spare parts, maintenance man-hours, transport costs, storage costs, part obsolete risks, etc.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] But, as GM and Toyota have belatedly discovered, TCO also includes the downstream liability costs when reliability calculations have not sufficiently or accurately addressed customers' bodily risks.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Often a trade-off is needed between the two.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] There might be a maximum ratio between availability and cost of ownership.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The testability of a system should also be addressed in the plan, as this is the link between reliability and maintainability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintenance strategy can influence the reliability of a system (e.g., by preventive and/or predictive maintenance), although it can never bring it above the inherent reliability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The reliability plan should clearly provide a strategy for availability control.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Whether only availability or also cost of ownership is more important depends on the use of the system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] A proper reliability plan should always address RAMT analysis in its total context.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] RAMT stands for reliability, availability, maintainability/maintenance, and testability in the context of the customer's needs.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] For any system, one of the first tasks of reliability engineering is to adequately specify the reliability and maintainability requirements allocated from the overall availability needs and, more importantly, derived from proper design failure analysis or preliminary prototype test results.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Clear requirements (able to be designed to) should constrain the designers from designing particular unreliable items/constructions/interfaces/systems.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Setting only availability, reliability, testability, or maintainability targets (e.g., max. failure rates) is not appropriate.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] This is a broad misunderstanding about Reliability Requirements Engineering.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements address the system itself, including test and assessment requirements, and associated tasks and documentation.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements are included in the appropriate system or subsystem requirements specifications, test plans, and contract statements.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The creation of proper lower-level requirements is critical.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The provision of only quantitative minimum targets (e.g., Mean Time Between Failure (MTBF) values or failure rates) is not sufficient for different reasons.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Compare this problem with the continuous (re-)balancing of, for example, lower-level-system mass requirements in the development of an aircraft, which is already often a big undertaking.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Notice that in this case, masses do only differ in terms of only some %, are not a function of time, and the data is non-probabilistic and available already in CAD models.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] In the case of reliability, the levels of unreliability (failure rates) may change with factors of decades (multiples of 10) as a result of very minor deviations in design, process, or anything else.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The information is often not available without huge uncertainties within the development phase.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] This makes this allocation problem almost impossible to do in a useful, practical, valid manner that does not result in massive over- or under-specification.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] A pragmatic approach is therefore needed—for example: the use of general levels/classes of quantitative requirements depending only on severity of failure effects.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, the validation of results is a far more subjective task than any other type of requirement.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] (Quantitative) reliability parameters—in terms of MTBF—are by far the most uncertain design parameters in any design.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, reliability design requirements should drive a (system or part) design to incorporate features that prevent failures from occurring, or limit consequences from failure in the first place.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Not only would it aid in some predictions, this effort would keep from distracting the engineering effort into a kind of accounting work.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] A design requirement should be precise enough so that a designer can "design to" it and can also prove—through analysis or testing—that the requirement has been achieved, and, if possible, within some a stated confidence.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Any type of reliability requirement should be detailed and could be derived from failure analysis (Finite-Element Stress and Fatigue analysis, Reliability Hazard Analysis, FTA, FMEA, Human Factor Analysis, Functional Hazard Analysis, etc.) or any type of reliability testing.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, requirements are needed for verification tests (e.g., required overload stresses) and test time needed.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] To derive these requirements in an effective manner, a systems engineering-based risk assessment and mitigation logic should be used.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Robust hazard log systems must be created that contain detailed information on why and how systems could or have failed.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Requirements are to be derived and tracked in this way.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] These practical design requirements shall drive the design and not be used only for verification purposes.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements (often design constraints) are in this way derived from failure analysis or preliminary tests.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding of this difference compared to only purely quantitative (logistic) requirement specification (e.g., Failure Rate / MTBF target) is paramount in the development of successful (complex) systems.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintainability requirements address the costs of repairs as well as repair time.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Testability (not to be confused with test requirements) requirements provide the link between reliability and maintainability and should address detectability of failure modes (on a particular system level), isolation levels, and the creation of diagnostics (procedures).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] As indicated above, reliability engineers should also address requirements for various reliability tasks and documentation during system development, testing, production, and operation.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements are generally specified in the contract statement of work and depend on how much leeway the customer wishes to provide to the contractor.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability tasks include various analyses, planning, and failure reporting.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Task selection depends on the criticality of the system as well as cost.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] A safety-critical system may require a formal failure reporting and review process throughout development, whereas a non-critical system may rely on final test reports.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability program tasks are documented in reliability program standards, such as MIL-STD-785 and IEEE 1332.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure reporting analysis and corrective action systems are a common approach for product/process reliability monitoring.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] However, humans are also very good at detecting such failures, correcting them, and improvising when abnormal situations occur.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Therefore, policies that completely rule out human actions in design and production processes to improve reliability may not be effective.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Some tasks are better performed by humans and some are better performed by machines.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, human errors in management; the organization of data and information; or the misuse or abuse of items, may also contribute to unreliability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] This is the core reason why high levels of reliability for complex systems can only be achieved by following a robust systems engineering process with proper planning and execution of the validation and verification tasks.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] This also includes the careful organization of data and information sharing and creating a "reliability culture", in the same way, that having a "safety culture" is paramount in the development of safety-critical systems.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] For existing systems, it is arguable that any attempt by a responsible program to correct the root cause of discovered failures may render the initial MTBF estimate invalid, as new assumptions (themselves subject to high error levels) of the effect of this correction must be made.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Another practical issue is the general unavailability of detailed failure data, with those available often featuring inconsistent filtering of failure (feedback) data, and ignoring statistical errors (which are very high for rare events like reliability related failures).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Very clear guidelines must be present to count and compare failures related to different type of root-causes (e.g. manufacturing-, maintenance-, transport-, system-induced or inherent design failures).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Comparing different types of causes may lead to incorrect estimations and incorrect business decisions about the focus of improvement.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] To perform a proper quantitative reliability prediction for systems may be difficult and very expensive if done by testing.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] At the individual part-level, reliability results can often be obtained with comparatively high confidence, as testing of many sample parts might be possible using the available testing budget.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] However, these tests may lack validity at a system-level due to assumptions made at part-level testing.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] These authors emphasized the importance of initial part- or system-level testing until failure, and to learn from such failures to improve the system or part.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The general conclusion is drawn that an accurate and absolute prediction – by either field-data comparison or testing – of reliability is in most cases not possible.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] An exception might be failures due to wear-out problems such as fatigue failures.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] In the introduction of MIL-STD-785 it is written that reliability prediction should be used with great caution, if not used solely for comparison in trade-off studies.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Design for Reliability (DfR) is a process that encompasses tools and procedures to ensure that a product meets its reliability requirements, under its use environment, for the duration of its lifetime.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is implemented in the design stage of a product to proactively improve product reliability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is often used as part of an overall Design for Excellence (DfX) strategy.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability design begins with the development of a (system) model.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability and availability models use block diagrams and Fault Tree Analysis to provide a graphical means of evaluating the relationships between different parts of the system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] These models may incorporate predictions based on failure rates taken from historical data.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] While the (input data) predictions are often not accurate in an absolute sense, they are valuable to assess relative differences in design alternatives.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability parameters, for example Mean time to repair (MTTR), can also be used as inputs for such models.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The most important fundamental initiating causes and failure mechanisms are to be identified and analyzed with engineering tools.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] A diverse set of practical guidance as to performance and reliability should be provided to designers so that they can generate low-stressed designs and products that protect, or are protected against, damage and excessive wear.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Proper validation of input loads (requirements) may be needed, in addition to verification for reliability "performance" by testing.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] One of the most important design techniques is redundancy.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] This means that if one part of the system fails, there is an alternate success path, such as a backup system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason why this is the ultimate design choice is related to the fact that high-confidence reliability evidence for new parts or systems is often not available, or is extremely expensive to obtain.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] By combining redundancy, together with a high level of failure monitoring, and the avoidance of common cause failures; even a system with relatively poor single-channel (part) reliability, can be made highly reliable at a system level (up to mission critical reliability).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] No testing of reliability has to be required for this.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Redundancy can also be applied in systems engineering by double checking requirements, data, designs, calculations, software, and tests to overcome systematic failures.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Another effective way to deal with reliability issues is to perform analysis that predicts degradation, enabling the prevention of unscheduled downtime events / failures.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] RCM (Reliability Centered Maintenance) programs can be used for this.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] For electronic assemblies, there has been an increasing shift towards a different approach called physics of failure.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] This technique relies on understanding the physical static and dynamic failure mechanisms.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The material or component can be re-designed to reduce the probability of failure and to make it more robust against such variations.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Another common design technique is component derating: i.e. selecting components whose specifications significantly exceed the expected stress levels, such as using heavier gauge electrical wire than might normally be specified for the expected electric current.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Results from these methods are presented during reviews of part or system design, and logistics.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is just one requirement among many for a complex part or system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Engineering trade-off studies are used to determine the optimum balance between reliability requirements and other constraints.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineers, whether using quantitative or qualitative methods to describe a failure or hazard, rely on language to pinpoint the risks and enable issues to be solved.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The language used must help create an orderly description of the function/item/system and its complex surrounding as it relates to the failure of these functions/items/systems.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems engineering is very much about finding the correct words to describe the problem (and related risks), so that they can be readily solved via engineering solutions.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Jack Ring said that a systems engineer's job is to "language the project." (Ring et al.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] 2000) For part/system failures, reliability engineers should concentrate more on the "why and how", rather that predicting "when".
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding "why" a failure has occurred (e.g. due to over-stressed components or manufacturing issues) is far more likely to lead to improvement in the designs and processes used than quantifying "when" a failure is likely to occur (e.g. via determining MTBF).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] To do this, first the reliability hazards relating to the part/system need to be classified and ordered (based on some form of qualitative and quantitative logic if possible) to allow for more efficient assessment and eventual improvement.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] This is partly done in pure language and proposition logic, but also based on experience with similar items.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] This can for example be seen in descriptions of events in fault tree analysis, FMEA analysis, and hazard (tracking) logs.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] In this sense language and proper grammar (part of qualitative analysis) plays an important role in reliability engineering, just like it does in safety engineering or in-general within systems engineering.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Correct use of language can also be key to identifying or reducing the risks of human error, which are often the root cause of many failures.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] This can include proper instructions in maintenance manuals, operation manuals, emergency procedures, and others to prevent systematic human errors that may result in system failures.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability modeling is the process of predicting or understanding the reliability of a component or system prior to its implementation.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Two types of analysis that are often used to model a complete system's availability behavior including effects from logistics issues like spare part provisioning, transport and manpower are fault tree analysis and reliability block diagrams.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] At a component level, the same types of analyses can be used together with others.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The input for the models can come from many sources including testing; prior operational experience; field data; as well as data handbooks from similar or related industries.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Regardless of source, all model input data must be used with great caution, as predictions are only valid in cases where the same product was used in the same context.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] As such, predictions are often only used to help compare alternatives.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is defined as the probability that a device will perform its intended function during a specified period of time under stated conditions.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] where $f(x)\!$ is the failure probability density function and t is the length of the period of time (which is assumed to start from time zero).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability applies to a specified period of time.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] In practical terms, this means that a system has a specified chance that it will operate without failure before time $T\!$ .
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering ensures that components and materials will meet the requirements during the specified time.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Note that units other than time may sometimes be used (e.g.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is restricted to operation under stated (or explicitly defined) conditions.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] This constraint is necessary because it is impossible to design a system for unlimited conditions.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] A Mars rover will have different specified conditions than a family car.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The operating environment must be addressed during design and testing.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] That same rover may be required to operate in varying conditions requiring additional scrutiny.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Two notable references on reliability theory and its mathematical and statistical foundations are Barlow, R.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Often, knowledge of the statistical dependence between component failures is unknown or only partially constrained.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] When it is desired to model such incomplete knowledge, reliability theory allows for analyses that characterize ranges or bounds on system failure probabilities rather than unique distributions, particularly for small multi-component systems.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Quantitative requirements are specified using reliability parameters.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability parameter is the mean time to failure (MTTF), which can also be specified as the failure rate (this is expressed as a frequency or conditional probability density function (PDF)) or the number of failures during a given period.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] These parameters may be useful for higher system levels and systems that are operated frequently (i.e. vehicles, machinery, and electronic equipment).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability increases as the MTTF increases.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The MTTF is usually specified in hours, but can also be used with other units of measurement, such as miles or cycles.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Using MTTF values on lower system levels can be very misleading, especially if they do not specify the associated Failures Modes and Mechanisms (The F in MTTF).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] In other cases, reliability is specified as the probability of mission success.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] For example, reliability of a scheduled aircraft flight can be specified as a dimensionless probability or a percentage, as often used in system safety engineering.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] A special case of mission success is the single-shot device or system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] These are devices or systems that remain relatively dormant and only operate once.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Examples include automobile airbags, thermal batteries and missiles.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot reliability is specified as a probability of one-time success or is subsumed into a related parameter.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot missile reliability may be specified as a requirement for the probability of a hit.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] For such systems, the probability of failure on demand (PFD) is the reliability measure – this is actually an "unavailability" number.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] The PFD is derived from failure rate (a frequency of occurrence) and mission time for non-repairable systems.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] For repairable systems, it is obtained from failure rate, mean-time-to-repair (MTTR), and test interval.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] This measure may not be unique for a given system as this measure depends on the kind of demand.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] In addition to system level requirements, reliability requirements may be specified for critical subsystems.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p01] In most cases, reliability parameters are specified with appropriate statistical confidence intervals.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of **reliability testing** or **reliability verification** is to discover potential problems with the design as early as possible and, ultimately, provide confidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability of the product in all environments such as expected use, transportation, or storage during the specified lifespan should be considered.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability verification is also called reliability testing, which refers to the use of modeling, statistics, and other methods to evaluate the reliability of the product based on the product's life span and expected performance.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Most product on the market requires reliability testing, such as automotive, integrated circuit, heavy machinery used to mine nature resources, Aircraft auto software.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at several levels and there are different types of testing.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Complex systems may be tested at component, circuit board, unit, assembly, subsystem and system levels.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] (The test level nomenclature varies among applications.) For example, performing environmental stress screening tests at lower levels, such as piece parts or small assemblies, catches problems before they cause failures at higher levels.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing proceeds during each level of integration through full-up system testing, developmental testing, and operational testing, thereby reducing program risk.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] However, testing does not mitigate unreliability risk.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] With each test both statistical type I and type II errors could be made, depending on sample size, test time, assumptions and the needed discrimination ratio.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] There is risk of incorrectly rejecting a good design (type I error) and the risk of incorrectly accepting a bad design (type II error).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] It is not always feasible to test all system requirements.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Some systems are prohibitively expensive to test; some failure modes may take years to observe; some complex interactions result in a huge number of possible test cases; and some tests require the use of limited test ranges or other resources.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, different approaches to testing can be used, such as (highly) accelerated life testing, design of experiments, and simulations.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired level of statistical confidence also plays a role in reliability testing.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence is increased by increasing either the test time or the number of items tested.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test plans are designed to achieve the specified reliability at the specified confidence level with the minimum number of test units and test time.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Different test plans result in different levels of risk to the producer and consumer.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired reliability, statistical confidence, and risk levels for each side influence the ultimate test plan.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The customer and developer should agree in advance on how reliability requirements will be tested.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] A key aspect of reliability testing is to define "failure".
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Although this may seem obvious, there are many situations where it is not clear whether a failure is really the fault of the system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Variations in test conditions, operator differences, weather and unexpected situations create differences between the customer and the system developer.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] One strategy to address this issue is to use a scoring conference process.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] A scoring conference includes representatives from the customer, the developer, the test organization, the reliability organization, and sometimes independent observers.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The scoring conference process is defined in the statement of work.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Each test case is considered by the group and "scored" as a success or failure.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] This scoring is the official result used by the reliability engineer.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] As part of the requirements phase, the reliability engineer develops a test strategy with the customer.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The test strategy makes trade-offs between the needs of the reliability organization, which wants as much data as possible, and constraints such as cost, schedule and available resources.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Test plans and procedures are developed for each reliability test, and results are documented.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing is common in the Photonics industry.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Examples of reliability tests of lasers are life test and burn-in.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] These tests consist of the highly accelerated aging, under controlled conditions, of a group of lasers.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The data collected from these life tests are used to predict laser life expectancy under the intended operating characteristics.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The product life span can be split into four different for analysis.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Useful life is the estimated economic life of the product, which is defined as the time can be used before the cost of repair do not justify the continue use to the product.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Warranty life is the product should perform the function within the specified time period.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Design life is where during the design of the product, designer take into consideration on the life time of competitive product and customer desire and ensure that the product do not result in customer dissatisfaction.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test requirements can follow from any analysis for which the first estimate of failure probability, failure mode or effect needs to be justified.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Evidence can be generated with some level of confidence by testing.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] With software-based systems, the probability is a mix of software and hardware-based failures.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing reliability requirements is problematic for several reasons.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] A single test is in most cases insufficient to generate enough statistical data.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Multiple tests or long-duration tests are usually very expensive.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Some tests are simply impractical, and environmental conditions can be hard to predict over a systems life-cycle.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is used to design a realistic and affordable test program that provides empirical evidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence levels are used to address some of these concerns.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] A certain parameter is expressed along with a corresponding confidence level: for example, an MTBF of 1000 hours at 90% confidence level.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] From this specification, the reliability engineer can, for example, design a test with explicit criteria for the number of hours and number of failures until the requirement is met or failed.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The combination of required reliability level and required confidence level greatly affects the development cost and the risk to both the customer and producer.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Care is needed to select the best combination of requirements—e.g. cost-effectiveness.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at various levels, such as component, subsystem and system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems that must last many years, accelerated life tests may be needed.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] A systematic approach to reliability testing is to, first, determine reliability goal, then do tests that are linked to performance and determine the reliability of the product.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability verification test in modern industries should clearly determine how they relate to the product's overall reliability performance and how individual tests impact the warranty cost and customer satisfaction.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of accelerated life testing (ALT test) is to induce field failure in the laboratory at a much faster rate by providing a harsher, but nonetheless representative, environment.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] In such a test, the product is expected to fail in the lab just as it would have failed in the field—but in much less time.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability is a special aspect of reliability engineering.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] It focuses on foundations and techniques to make software more reliable, i.e., resilient to faults.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] System reliability, by definition, includes all parts of the system, including hardware, software, supporting infrastructure (including critical external interfaces), operators and procedures.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Traditionally, reliability engineering focuses on critical hardware parts of the system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Since the widespread use of digital integrated circuit technology, software has become an increasingly critical part of most electronics and, hence, nearly all present day systems.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Therefore, software reliability has gained prominence within the field of system reliability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] There are significant differences, however, in how software and hardware behave.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Most hardware unreliability is the result of a component or material failure that results in the system not performing its intended function.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Repairing or replacing the hardware component restores the system to its original operating state.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] However, software does not fail in the same sense that hardware fails.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software unreliability is the result of unanticipated results of software operations.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Even relatively small software programs can have astronomically large combinations of inputs and states that are infeasible to exhaustively test.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Restoring software to its original state only works until the same combination of inputs and states results in the same unintended result.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering must take this into account.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] As with hardware, software reliability depends on good requirements, design and implementation.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering relies heavily on a disciplined software engineering process to anticipate and design against unintended consequences.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] There is more overlap between software quality engineering and software reliability engineering than between hardware quality and reliability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] A good software development plan is a key aspect of the software reliability program.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The software development plan describes the design and coding standards, peer reviews, unit tests, configuration management, software metrics and software models to be used during software development.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] In modern distributed and microservices-based systems, reliability considerations increasingly extend beyond component-level correctness to include the behavior of applications at the business-logic level.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] It addresses scenarios in which individual system components may appear operational, while failures arise from service interactions or logic errors, potentially leading to degraded user experience or incorrect outcomes.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Practices associated with application-level reliability include end-to-end observability, synthetic transaction testing, and validation of business-critical processes, complementing traditional infrastructure-focused reliability methods.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] A common reliability metric is the number of software faults per line of code (FLOC), usually expressed as faults per thousand lines of code.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric, along with software execution time, is key to most software reliability models and estimates.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The theory is that the software reliability increases as the number of faults (or fault density) decreases.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Establishing a direct connection between fault density and mean-time-between-failure is difficult, however, because of the way software faults are distributed in the code, their severity, and the probability of the combination of inputs necessary to encounter the fault.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Nevertheless, fault density serves as a useful indicator for the reliability engineer.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Other software metrics, such as complexity, are also used.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric remains controversial, since changes in software development and verification practices can have dramatic impact on overall defect rates.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Software testing is an important aspect of software reliability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Even the best software development process results in some software faults that are nearly undetectable until tested.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Software is tested at several levels, starting with individual units, through integration and full-up system testing.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] All phases of testing, software faults are discovered, corrected, and re-tested.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability estimates are updated based on the fault density and other metrics.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] At a system level, mean-time-between-failure data can be collected and used to estimate reliability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Unlike hardware, performing exactly the same test on exactly the same software configuration does not provide increased statistical confidence.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software reliability uses different metrics, such as code coverage.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The Software Engineering Institute's capability maturity model is a common means of assessing the overall software development process for reliability and quality purposes.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Structural reliability or the reliability of structures is the application of reliability theory to the behavior of structures.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] It is used in both the design and maintenance of different types of structures including concrete and steel structures.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] In structural reliability studies both loads and resistances are modeled as probabilistic variables.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Using this approach the probability of failure of a structure is calculated.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability for safety and reliability for availability are often closely related.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Lost availability of an engineering system can cost money.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] If a subway system is unavailable the subway operator will lose money for each hour the system is down.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The subway operator will lose more money if safety is compromised.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The definition of reliability is tied to a probability of not encountering a failure.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] A failure can cause loss of safety, loss of availability or both.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] It is undesirable to lose safety or availability in a critical system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is concerned with overall minimisation of failures that could lead to financial losses for the responsible entity, whereas safety engineering focuses on minimising a specific set of failure types that in general could lead to loss of life, injury or damage to equipment.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety engineering is often highly specific, relating only to certain tightly regulated industries, applications, or areas.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] It primarily focuses on system safety hazards that could lead to severe accidents including: loss of life; destruction of equipment; or environmental damage.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] As such, the related system functional reliability requirements are often extremely high.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Although it deals with unwanted failures in the same sense as reliability engineering, it, however, has less of a focus on direct costs, and is not concerned with post-failure repair actions.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Another difference is the level of impact of failures on society, leading to a tendency for strict control by governments or regulatory bodies (e.g. nuclear, aerospace, defense, rail and oil industries).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety can be increased using a 2oo2 cross checked redundant system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Availability can be increased by using "1oo2" (1 out of 2) redundancy at a part or system level.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] If both redundant elements disagree the more permissive element will maximize availability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] A 1oo2 system should never be relied on for safety.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Fault-tolerant systems often rely on additional redundancy (e.g.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] 2oo3 voting logic) where multiple redundant elements must agree on a potentially unsafe action before it is performed.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] This increases both availability and safety at a system level.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] This is common practice in aerospace systems that need continued availability and do not have a fail-safe mode.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The above example of a 2oo3 fault tolerant system increases both mission reliability as well as safety.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] However, the "basic" reliability of the system will in this case still be lower than a non-redundant (1oo1) or 2oo2 system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Basic reliability engineering covers all failures, including those that might not result in system failure, but do result in additional cost due to: maintenance repair actions; logistics; spare parts etc.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] For example, replacement or repair of 1 faulty channel in a 2oo3 voting system, (the system is still operating, although with one failed channel it has actually become a 2oo2 system) is contributing to basic unreliability but not mission unreliability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] As an example, the failure of the tail-light of an aircraft will not prevent the plane from flying (and so is not considered a mission failure), but it does need to be remedied (with a related cost, and so does contribute to the basic unreliability levels).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] When using fault tolerant (redundant) systems or systems that are equipped with protection functions, detectability of failures and avoidance of common cause failures becomes paramount for safe functioning and/or mission reliability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality often focuses on manufacturing defects during the warranty phase.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability looks at the failure intensity over the whole life of a product or engineering system from commissioning to decommissioning.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma has its roots in statistical control in quality of manufacturing.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is a specialty part of systems engineering.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The systems engineering process is a discovery process that is often unlike a manufacturing process.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] A manufacturing process is often focused on repetitive activities that achieve high quality outputs with minimum cost and time.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The everyday usage term "quality of a product" is loosely taken to mean its inherent degree of excellence.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] In industry, a more precise definition of quality as "conformance to requirements or specifications at the start of use" is used.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Assuming the final product specification adequately captures the original requirements and customer/system needs, the quality level can be measured as the fraction of product units shipped that meet specifications.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Manufactured goods quality often focuses on the number of warranty claims during the warranty period.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is a snapshot at the start of life through the warranty period and is related to the control of lower-level product specifications.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] This includes time-zero defects i.e. where manufacturing mistakes escaped final Quality Control.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] In theory the quality level might be described by a single fraction of defective products.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability, as a part of systems engineering, acts as more of an ongoing assessment of failure rates over many years.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Theoretically, all items will fail over an infinite period of time.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Defects that appear over time are referred to as reliability fallout.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] To describe reliability fallout a probability model that describes the fraction fallout over time is needed.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] This is known as the life distribution model.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of these reliability issues may be due to inherent design issues, which may exist even though the product conforms to specifications.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Even items that are produced perfectly will fail over time due to one or more failure mechanisms (e.g. due to human error or mechanical, electrical, and chemical factors).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] These reliability issues can also be influenced by acceptable levels of variation during initial production.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality and reliability are, therefore, related to manufacturing.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability is more targeted towards clients who are focused on failures throughout the whole life of the product such as the military, airlines or railroads.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Items that do not conform to product specification will generally do worse in terms of reliability (having a lower MTTF), but this does not always have to be the case.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The full mathematical quantification (in statistical models) of this combined relation is in general very difficult or even practically impossible.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] In cases where manufacturing variances can be effectively reduced, six sigma tools have been shown to be useful to find optimal process solutions which can increase quality and reliability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma may also help to design products that are more robust to manufacturing induced failures and infant mortality defects in engineering systems and manufactured product.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] In contrast with Six Sigma, reliability engineering solutions are generally found by focusing on reliability testing and system design.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Furthermore, reliability engineering uses system-level solutions, like designing redundant and fault-tolerant systems for situations with high availability needs (see Reliability engineering vs Safety engineering above).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Note: A "defect" in six-sigma/quality literature is not the same as a "failure" (Field failure | e.g. fractured item) in reliability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] A six-sigma/quality defect refers generally to non-conformance with a requirement (e.g. basic functionality or a key dimension).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Items can, however, fail over time, even if these requirements are all fulfilled.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is generally not concerned with asking the crucial question "are the requirements actually correct?", whereas reliability is.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Once systems or parts are being produced, reliability engineering attempts to monitor, assess, and correct deficiencies.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Monitoring includes electronic and visual surveillance of critical parameters identified during the fault tree analysis design stage.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Data collection is highly dependent on the nature of the system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Most large organizations have quality control groups that collect failure data on vehicles, equipment and machinery.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Consumer product failures are often tracked by the number of returns.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems in dormant storage or on standby, it is necessary to establish a formal surveillance program to inspect and test random samples.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Any changes to the system, such as field upgrades or recall repairs, require additional reliability testing to ensure the reliability of the modification.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Since it is not possible to anticipate all the failure modes of a given system, especially ones with a human element, failures will occur.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability program also includes a systematic root cause analysis that identifies the causal relationships involved in the failure such that effective corrective actions may be implemented.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] When possible, system failures and corrective actions are reported to the reliability engineering organization.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the most common methods to apply to a reliability operational assessment are failure reporting, analysis, and corrective action systems (FRACAS).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] This systematic approach develops a reliability, safety, and logistics assessment based on failure/incident reporting, management, analysis, and corrective/preventive actions.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Organizations today are adopting this method and utilizing commercial systems (such as Web-based FRACAS applications) that enable them to create a failure/incident data repository from which statistics can be derived to view accurate and genuine reliability, safety, and quality metrics.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] It is extremely important for an organization to adopt a common FRACAS system for all end items.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Also, it should allow test results to be captured in a practical way.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Failure to adopt one easy-to-use (in terms of ease of data-entry for field engineers and repair shop engineers) and easy-to-maintain integrated system is likely to result in a failure of the FRACAS program itself.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the common outputs from a FRACAS system include Field MTBF, MTTR, spares consumption, reliability growth, failure/incidents distribution by type, location, part no., serial no., and symptom.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The use of past data to predict the reliability of new comparable systems/items can be misleading as reliability is a function of the context of use and can be affected by small changes in design/manufacturing.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Systems of any significant complexity are developed by organizations of people, such as a commercial company or a government agency.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability engineering organization must be consistent with the company's organizational structure.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] For small, non-critical systems, reliability engineering may be informal.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] As complexity grows, the need arises for a formal reliability function.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability is important to the customer, the customer may even specify certain aspects of the reliability organization.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] There are several common types of reliability organizations.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] The project manager or chief engineer may employ one or more reliability engineers directly.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] In larger organizations, there is usually a product assurance or specialty engineering organization, which may include reliability, maintainability, quality, safety, human factors, logistics, etc.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] In such case, the reliability engineer reports to the product assurance manager or specialty engineering manager.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] In some cases, a company may wish to establish an independent reliability organization.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] This is desirable to ensure that the system reliability, which is often expensive and time-consuming, is not unduly slighted due to budget and schedule pressures.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, the reliability engineer works for the project day-to-day, but is actually employed and paid by a separate organization within the company.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability engineering is critical to early system design, it has become common for reliability engineers, however, the organization is structured, to work as part of an integrated product team.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Some universities offer graduate degrees in reliability engineering.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Other reliability professionals typically have an engineering, statistics, math, or physics degree from a university or college program.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Many engineering programs offer reliability courses, and some universities have entire reliability engineering programs.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability engineer must be registered as a professional engineer by the state or province by law, but not all reliability professionals are engineers.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineers are required in systems where public safety is at risk.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] There are many professional conferences and industry training programs available for reliability engineers.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/reliability-engineering-p02] Several professional organizations exist for reliability engineers, including the American Society for Quality Reliability Division (ASQ-RD), the IEEE Reliability Society, the American Society for Quality (ASQ), and the Society of Reliability Engineers (SRE).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] There is now more dependence on these systems as a result of modernization.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] For example, to carry out their regular daily tasks, hospitals and data centers need their systems to be highly available.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Availability refers to the ability of the user to access a service or system, whether to submit new work, update or modify existing work, or retrieve the results of previous work.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] If a user cannot access the system, it is considered *unavailable from the user's perspective*.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] The term *downtime* is generally used to refer to describe periods when a system is unavailable.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] As such, network resilience touches a very wide range of topics.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] In order to increase the resilience of a given communication network, the probable challenges and risks have to be identified and appropriate resilience metrics have to be defined for the service to be protected.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] The importance of network resilience is continuously increasing, as communication networks are becoming a fundamental component in the operation of critical infrastructures.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Consequently, recent efforts focus on interpreting and improving network and computing resilience with applications to critical infrastructures.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] As an example, one can consider as a resilience objective the provisioning of services over the network, instead of the services of the network itself.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] This may require coordinated response from both the network and from the services running on top of the network.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Resilience and survivability are interchangeably used according to the specific context of a given study.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] There are three principles of systems design in reliability engineering that can help achieve high availability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] In redundant systems, the crossover point itself tends to become a single point of failure.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Reliable systems must provide for reliable crossover.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] If the two principles above are observed, then a user may never see a failure – but the maintenance activity must.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] A distinction can be made between scheduled and unscheduled downtime.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Typically, scheduled downtime is a result of maintenance that is disruptive to system operation and usually cannot be avoided with a currently installed system design.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Scheduled downtime events might include patches to system software that require a reboot or system configuration changes that only take effect upon a reboot.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] In general, scheduled downtime is usually the result of some logical, management-initiated event.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Unscheduled downtime events typically arise from some physical event, such as a hardware or software failure or environmental anomaly.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] If users can be warned away from scheduled downtimes, then the distinction is useful.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] But if the requirement is for true high availability, then downtime is downtime whether or not it is scheduled.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Many computing sites exclude scheduled downtime from availability calculations, assuming that it has little or no impact upon the computing user community.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] By doing this, they can claim to have phenomenally high availability, which might give the illusion of continuous availability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] For certain systems, scheduled downtime does not matter, for example, system downtime at an office building after everybody has gone home for the night.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Availability is usually expressed as a percentage of uptime in a given year.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] The following table shows the downtime that will be allowed for a particular percentage of availability, presuming that the system is required to operate continuously.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Service level agreements often refer to monthly downtime or availability in order to calculate service credits to match monthly billing cycles.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] The following table shows the translation from a given availability percentage to the corresponding amount of time a system would be unavailable.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Availability is often quoted in terms of "nines", with 90% availability being called "one nine", 99% "two nines", 99.9% "three nines" and so on.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] As the number of nines gets larger, the availability targets get exponentially more stringent.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] The terms uptime and availability are often used interchangeably but do not always refer to the same thing.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] For example, a system can be "up" with its services not "available" in the case of a network outage.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Or a system undergoing software maintenance can be "available" to be worked on by a system administrator, but its services do not appear "up" to the end user or customer.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] A simple mnemonic rule states that *5 nines* allows approximately 5 minutes of downtime per year.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Variants can be derived by multiplying or dividing by 10: 4 nines is 50 minutes and 3 nines is 500 minutes.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] In the opposite direction, 6 nines is 0.5 minutes (30 sec) and 7 nines is 3 seconds.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Another memory trick to calculate the allowed downtime duration for an " n -nines" availability percentage is to use the formula $8.64\times 10^{4-n}$ seconds per day.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] For example, 90% ("one nine") yields the exponent $4-1=3$ , and therefore the allowed downtime is $8.64\times 10^{3}$ seconds per day.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Also, 99.999% ("five nines") gives the exponent $4-5=-1$ , and therefore the allowed downtime is $8.64\times 10^{-1}$ seconds per day.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Percentages of a particular order of magnitude are sometimes referred to by the number of nines or "class of nines" in the digits.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] For example, electricity that is delivered without interruptions (blackouts, brownouts or surges) 99.999% of the time would have 5 nines reliability, or class five.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] In particular, the term is used in connection with mainframes or enterprise computing, often as part of a service-level agreement.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Similarly, percentages ending in a 5 have conventional names, traditionally the number of nines, then "five", so 99.95% is "three nines five", abbreviated 3N5.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] This is casually referred to as "three and a half nines", but this is incorrect: a 5 is only a factor of 2, while a 9 is a factor of 10, so a 5 is 0.3 nines (per below formula: $\log _{10}2\approx 0.3$ ): 99.95% availability is 3.3 nines, not 3.5 nines.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] More simply, going from 99.9% availability to 99.95% availability is a factor of 2 (0.1% to 0.05% unavailability), but going from 99.95% to 99.99% availability is a factor of 5 (0.05% to 0.01% unavailability), over twice as much.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] A similar measurement is sometimes used to describe the purity of substances.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] In general, the number of nines is not often used by a network engineer when modeling and measuring availability because it is hard to apply in formula.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] More often, the unavailability expressed as a probability (like 0.00001), or a downtime per year is quoted.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Availability specified as a number of nines is often seen in marketing documents.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] The use of the "nines" has been called into question, since it does not appropriately reflect that the impact of unavailability varies with its time of occurrence.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] For large amounts of 9s, the "unavailability" index (measure of downtime rather than uptime) is easier to handle.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] For example, this is why an "unavailability" rather than availability metric is used in hard disk or data link bit error rates.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Sometimes the humorous term "nine fives" (55.5555555%) is used to contrast with "five nines" (99.999%), though this is not an actual goal, but rather a sarcastic reference to something totally failing to meet any reasonable target.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Availability measurement is subject to some degree of interpretation.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] A system that has been up for 365 days in a non-leap year might have been eclipsed by a network failure that lasted for 9 hours during a peak usage period; the user community will see the system as unavailable, whereas the system administrator will claim 100% uptime.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] However, given the true definition of availability, the system will be approximately 99.9% available, or three nines (8751 hours of available time out of 8760 hours per non-leap year).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Also, systems experiencing performance problems are often deemed partially or entirely unavailable by users, even when the systems are continuing to function.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Similarly, unavailability of select application functions might go unnoticed by administrators yet be devastating to users – a true availability measure is holistic.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Availability must be measured to be determined, ideally with comprehensive monitoring tools ("instrumentation") that are themselves highly available.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] An alternative metric is mean time between failures (MTBF).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Recovery time (or estimated time of repair (ETR), also known as recovery time objective (RTO) is closely related to availability, that is the total time required for a planned outage or the time required to fully recover from an unplanned outage.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Another metric is mean time to recovery (MTTR).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Recovery time could be infinite with certain system designs and failures, i.e. full recovery is impossible.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] One such example is a fire or flood that destroys a data center and its systems when there is no secondary disaster recovery data center.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Another related concept is data availability, that is the degree to which databases and other information storage systems faithfully record and report system transactions.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Information management often focuses separately on data availability, or Recovery Point Objective, in order to determine acceptable (or actual) data loss with various failure events.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Some users can tolerate application service interruptions but cannot tolerate data loss.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] A service level agreement ("SLA") formalizes an organization's availability objectives and requirements.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] High availability is one of the primary requirements of the control systems in unmanned vehicles and autonomous maritime vessels.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] If the controlling system becomes unavailable, the Ground Combat Vehicle (GCV) or ASW Continuous Trail Unmanned Vessel (ACTUV) would be lost.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] On one hand, adding more components to an overall system design can undermine efforts to achieve high availability because complex systems inherently have more potential failure points and are more difficult to implement correctly.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] More advanced system designs allow for systems to be patched and upgraded without compromising service availability (see load balancing and failover).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] High availability requires less human intervention to restore operation in complex systems; the reason for this being that the most common cause for outages is human error.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] On the other hand, redundancy is used to create systems with high levels of availability (e.g. popular ecommerce websites).
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] In this case it is required to have high levels of failure detectability and avoidance of common cause failures.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] If redundant parts are used in parallel and have independent failure (e.g. by not being within the same data center), they can exponentially increase the availability and make the overall system highly available.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] So for example if each of your components has only 50% availability, by using 10 of components in parallel, you can achieve 99.9023% availability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Two kinds of redundancy are passive redundancy and active redundancy.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Passive redundancy is used to achieve high availability by including enough excess capacity in the design to accommodate a performance decline.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] The simplest example is a boat with two separate engines driving two separate propellers.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] The boat continues toward its destination despite failure of a single engine or propeller.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] A more complex example is multiple redundant power generation facilities within a large system involving electric power transmission.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Malfunction of single components is not considered to be a failure unless the resulting performance decline exceeds the specification limits for the entire system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Active redundancy is used in complex systems to achieve high availability with no performance decline.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Multiple items of the same kind are incorporated into a design that includes a method to detect failure and automatically reconfigure the system to bypass failed items using a voting scheme.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] This is used with complex computing systems that are linked.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Internet routing is derived from early work by Birman and Joseph in this area.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Active redundancy may introduce more complex failure modes into a system, such as continuous system reconfiguration due to faulty voting logic.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Fault instrumentation can be used in systems with limited redundancy to achieve high availability.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Maintenance actions occur during brief periods of downtime only after a fault indicator activates.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Failure is only significant if this occurs during a mission critical period.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Modeling and simulation is used to evaluate the theoretical reliability for large systems.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] The outcome of this kind of model is used to evaluate different design options.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] A model of the entire system is created, and the model is stressed by removing components.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] Redundancy simulation involves the N-x criteria.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] N represents the total number of components in the system. x is the number of components used to stress the system.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] N-1 means the model is stressed by evaluating performance with all possible combinations where one component is faulted.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] N-2 means the model is stressed by evaluating performance with all possible combinations where two component are faulted simultaneously.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] A survey among academic availability experts in 2010 ranked reasons for unavailability of enterprise IT systems.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] A book on the factors themselves was published in 2003.
[src:chaos-engineering-tools/resilience-network] In a 1998 report from IBM Global Services, unavailable systems were estimated to have cost American businesses $4.54 billion in 1996, due to lost productivity and revenues.
